This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of computational linguistics (cs.CL) because it deals with the meaning and comprehension of language, specifically generic language. It also uses probabilistic models of language understanding, which is a common approach in computational linguistics. Additionally, the paper may also belong to the sub-categories of artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG) because of the use of probabilistic models. The sub-category of cryptography and security (cs.CR) is also a possibility because the paper discusses the subjective beliefs that underlie the meaning of generic language, which could have implications for security and privacy. Finally, the sub-category of computational complexity (cs.CC) is a possibility because the paper discusses the flexibility in usage of generics, which could have implications for the complexity of language understanding.
